### HashSet in Rust

`HashSet<T>` is a set data structure that stores unique values with no duplicates. It is implemented as a wrapper around `HashMap<T, ()>`.

---

### HashSet Operations

| Method | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| `HashSet::new()` | Create empty set |
| `insert(val)` | Add value |
| `remove(&val)` | Remove value |
| `contains(&val)` | Check if contains |
| `len()` | Number of elements |
| `union(&other)` | Union of two sets |
| `intersection(&other)` | Intersection of two sets |
| `difference(&other)` | Difference of two sets |
| `symmetric_difference(&other)` | Symmetric difference |

---

### Examples

```rust
use std::collections::HashSet;

let mut set = HashSet::new();
set.insert(1);
set.insert(2);
set.insert(3);
set.insert(1);  // no effect, already present

println!("Length: {}", set.len());  // 3

// Set operations
let a: HashSet<i32> = [1, 2, 3].iter().copied().collect();
let b: HashSet<i32> = [3, 4, 5].iter().copied().collect();

let union: HashSet<_> = a.union(&b).copied().collect();
let intersection: HashSet<_> = a.intersection(&b).copied().collect();
```

> **Key Point:** Use HashSet when you need fast membership checks and want to eliminate duplicates. The set operations (union, intersection, difference) return iterators, so use `.copied().collect()` to create new sets.

codeExample:
use std::collections::HashSet;

fn main() {
    let mut seen = HashSet::new();
    let items = vec!["a", "b", "a", "c", "b", "d"];

    for item in items {
        if seen.insert(item) {
            println!("First time seeing: {}", item);
        } else {
            println!("Already seen: {}", item);
        }
    }

    println!("Unique items: {:?}", seen);
}
